04765nam a22005535i 9780822398776DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223987767 a10.1515/97808223987762doi  a(DE-B1597)554362  a(OCoLC)1229161208  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPQ7082.N7bA87 1999 7aLIT0041002bisacsh1 aAvelar, Idelber, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Untimely Present :bPostdictatorial Latin American Fiction and the Task of Mourning /cIdelber Avelar. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Allegory and Mourning in Postdictatorship -- t1. OEDIPUS IN POST-AURATIC TIMES Modernization and Mourning in the Spanish American Boom -- t2.THE GENEALOGY OF A DEFEAT Latin American Culture under Dictatorship -- t3. COUNTERTRADITIONS The Allegorical Rewriting of the Past -- t4. ENCRYPTING RESTITUTION A Detective Story in the City of the Dead -- t5. PASTICHE, REPETITION, AND THE ANGEL OF HISTORY'S FORGED SIGNATURE -- t6. OVERCODIFICATION OF THE MARGINS Figures of the Eternal Return and the Apocalypse -- t7. BILDUNGSROMAN AT A STANDSTILL, OR THE WEAKENING OF STORYTELLING -- t8. THE UNMOURNED DEAD AND THE PROMISE OF RESTITUTION -- tAFTER WORD Postdictatorship and Postmodernity -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Untimely Present examines the fiction produced in the aftermath of the recent Latin American dictatorships, particularly those in Argentina, Brazil, and Chile. Idelber Avelar argues that through their legacy of social trauma and obliteration of history, these military regimes gave rise to unique and revealing practices of mourning that pervade the literature of this region. The theory of postdictatorial writing developed here is informed by a rereading of the links between mourning and mimesis in Plato, Nietzsche's notion of the untimely, Benjamin's theory of allegory, and psychoanalytic / deconstructive conceptions of mourning.Avelar starts by offering new readings of works produced before the dictatorship era, in what is often considered the boom of Latin American fiction. Distancing himself from previous celebratory interpretations, he understands the boom as a manifestation of mourning for literature's declining aura. Against this background, Avelar offers a reassessment of testimonial forms, social scientific theories of authoritarianism, current transformations undergone by the university, and an analysis of a number of novels by some of today's foremost Latin American writers-such as Ricardo Piglia, Silviano Santiago, Diamela Eltit, João Gilberto Noll, and Tununa Mercado. Avelar shows how the 'untimely' quality of these narratives is related to the position of literature itself, a mode of expression threatened with obsolescence.This book will appeal to scholars and students of Latin American literature and politics, cultural studies, and comparative literature, as well as to all those interested in the role of literature in postmodernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aDictatorshipzSouthern Cone of South AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLatin American fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezSouthern Cone of South America. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398776zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn